Leaf lifespan allometry

Sylvain Schmitt sylvain.schmitt@agroparistech.fr

2017-05-11

Introduction

TROLL model currently encompass Reichs 1991 and 1997 and Wrights 2004 allometries to estimate leaf lifespan with (Reich et al. 1991, 1997; Wright et al. 2004). But we have shown that Reichs allometries are underestimating leaf lifespan for low LMA species. Moreover simulations estimated unrealistically low aboveground biomass for low LMA species. We assumed Reichs allometries underestimation of leaf lifespan for low LMA species being the source of unrealistically low aboveground biomass inside TROLL simulations. We decided to find a better allometry with Wright et al. (2004) GLOPNET dataset.

Figure 1: Leaf mass per area (LMA), leaf nitrogen content (Nmass) and leaflifespan (LL). Leaf mass per area (LMA in \(g.m^{-2}\)), leaf nitrogen content (Nmass, in \(mg.g^-1\)) and leaf lifespan (LL in \(months\)) are taken in GLOPNET dataset from Wright et al. (2004).

First model

We tested different models and we kept the model with the best tradeoff between model complexity, convergence, likelihood, and prediction quality (see leaf lifespan model document). We found following model, named M1: \[M1~~ {LL_s}_j \sim \mathcal{logN}(\beta_0*e^{{\beta_1}_s*{LMA_s}_j - {\beta_2}_s*{Nmass_s}_j},\,\sigma)\,\] \[s=1,...,S_{=4}~, ~~j=1,...,n_s\] \[{\beta_i}_s \sim \mathcal{N}({\beta_i},\,\sigma_i)\,^I, ~~(\beta_i, \sigma, \sigma_i) \sim \mathcal{\Gamma}(0.001,\,0.001)\,^{2I+1}\]

Leaf lifespan (\(LL\)) is following a lognormal law with location \({\mu_s}_j\) and scale \(\sigma\). \(s\) represents the dataset used to do the fit between 1 and \(S=4\), it encompass environmental and protocol variations. \(j\) represents the observation for a given site \(s\). Location \({\mu_s}_j\) is the exponential from the difference between LMA and Nmass with parameters \({\beta_0}_s\), \({\beta_1}_s\), and \({\beta_2}_s\). Each \({\beta_i}_s\) is following a normal law located on \(\beta_i\) with scale \(\sigma_i\). Finally all \(beta_i\), \(\sigma\), and \(\sigma_i\) are assumed without presemption following gamma laws of parameters \(10^-2\), \(10^-2\).

Second model

Data gathering

We gathered data from TRY database to evaluate and improve previous model. We requested functional traits available in Bridge dataset and leaf lifespan for tropical species present in GLOPNET dataset and used in TROLL (see table 1). We currently obtained public data, which are used in subsequent analysis. We are waiting for restricted data to get an extended dataset and repeat the analysis.

Table 1: Functional traits gathered with TRY.

Name Trait Unit TRYcode
LL Leaf lifespan (longevity) month 12
SLA Leaf area per leaf dry mass (specific leaf area, SLA) \(m^2.kg^{-1}\) 11
N Leaf nitrogen (N) content per leaf dry mass \(mg.g^{-1}\) 15
P Leaf phosphorus (P) content per leaf dry mass \(mg.g^{-1}\) 14
wsg Stem dry mass per stem fresh volume (stem specific density) \(mg.mm^{-3}\) 4

Model

We compiled GLOPNET, TRY, and DRYAD databases to gather the biggest dataset. We kept dataset given by GLOPNET as origin dataset for observations. It correspond to leaf lifespan and also to LMA and Nmass in most of cases. We measured variable importance in functionnal traits to explain leaf lifespan with out-of bag method applied on a random forest (see Table 2).

Table 2: Variable importance calculated with out-of the bag method applied on a random forest. Leaf lifespan (LL in \(months\)) is taken in GLOPNET database from Wright et al. (2004). Leaf mass per area (LMA in \(g.m^{-2}\)), and leaf nitrogen content (Nmass, in \(mg.g^-1\)) are taken both in TRY (https://www.try-db.org) and GLOPNET databases. Wood specific gravity (wsg in ) is taken both in TRY and DRYAD databases.

LMA 103.39502 2183.717

wsg 52.80271 1475.523

We decided to add to model M1, wood specific gravity as a new predictor through a parameter \(\beta_3\) in a new model named M10. We removed dataset random effect on \(\beta_3\) due to the fact that all wood specific gravities were provided by DRYAD database. Due to a correlation between \(\beta_0\) and \(\beta_3\) in M10 (see figure 5), we tried also a model M11 without intercept \(\beta_0\). We then sampled all models with this composite dataset, and obtained following results :

Table 3: Model fit results for composite dataset. Data are taken from GLOPNET, TRY, and DRYAD datasets (see previous description). ML stand for maximum likelihood and RMSEP for root mean square error of prediction

M Model ML
M1 \({LL_s}_j \sim \mathcal{logN}(\beta_0 + {\beta_1}_s*{LMA_s}_j - {\beta_2}_s*{Nmass_s}_j,\,\sigma)\,\) 9.921572
M10 \({LL_s}_j \sim \mathcal{logN}(\beta_0 + {\beta_1}_s*{LMA_s}_j - {\beta_2}_s*{Nmass_s}_j + {\beta_3}*{wsg}_j,\,\sigma)\,\) 15.127427
M11 \({LL_s}_j \sim \mathcal{logN}({\beta_1}_s*{LMA_s}_j - {\beta_2}_s*{Nmass_s}_j + {\beta_3}*{wsg}_j,\,\sigma)\,\) 13.598262

Model M10 and M11 are both better than model M1 in likelihood and prediction quality (see table 3). Model M11 is even slightly better than model M10 in prediction quality (12.5 against 13.5). Finally model M10 has an higher likelihood of two points than model M11 but this is partly due to an over-fitting of model M10 which integrated one additionnal parameter. Consequently Aikaike Information Criterion advised to keep model M11 over model M10.

Posterior distributions and convergence

All model have correctly converged.

Figure 3: Parameters posterior ditribution. Light blue area represents 80% confidence interval, and vertical blue line the mean.

Figure 4: Parameters markov chains. Light grey area represents warmup iterations.

Parameters correlation

Model M10 have shown a correlation between parameters \(\beta_0\) and \(\beta_3\), responsible for the creation of model M11 (see previous paragraphs). Model M11 only show a slight link between \(\beta_1\) and \(\beta_3\) which can be considered as non significant.

Figure 5: Parameters pairs plot for model M10 and M11. Parameters density distribution, pairs plot and Pearsons coefficient of correlation.

Model predictions

We can denote that retained vector of parameters with maximum likelihood for model M11 is close to 95% confidence limit.

Figure 6: Leaflifespan predictions for model M11 with leaf mass per area (LMA), leaf nitrogen content (Nmass), wood specific gravity (wsg) and predicted versus observed values. Leaf lifespan (LL in \(months\)) is predicted with model M10 fit. Leaf mass per area (LMA in \(g.m^{-2}\)) and leaf nitrogen content (Nmass, in %), and wood specific gravity (wsg in \(mg.mm^{-3}\)) are taken in a composite dataset of GLOPNET, TRY and DRYAD datasets. Warning LMA (resp. Nmass and wsg) is not constant and depend on the closest point value for right (resp. center and left) graph.

\[M11:~~ LL = e^{0.017*LMA-0.103*Nmass + 1.94*wsg}\]

TROLL tests

We finally tested the new allometry obtained with M11 on TROLL data (figure 7) and with TROLL simulations (figure 8).

TROLL predictions

Minimum leaf lifespan is now above 3 months for model M11 with TROLL species dataset. Moreover lowest leaf lifespan species are not the one with the smallest LMA with new model. Lastly, model M11 variation of leaf lifespan is almost spanning all previous allometries prediciton on LMA axis.

Figure 7: Leaflifespan predictions for model different allometries with leaf mass per area (LMA), and leaf nitrogen content (Nmass), and wood specific gravity (wsg). Leaf lifespan (LL in \(months\)) is predicted with model M1, M10, and M11 fits or Reichs and Wrights allometries (Reich et al. 1991). Leaf mass per area (LMA in \(g.m^{-2}\)) leaf nitrogen content (Nmass, in %) , and wood specific gravity (wsg in \(mg.mm^{-3}\)) are taken in BRIDGE dataset used by TROLL (Marchaux & Chave).

TROLL simulation

Simulations are validating that this new allometry resolve the issue of unrealistically low aboveground biomass for low LMA species due to an early edath of individuals inside simulations. For instance with this allometry Symphonia sp 1 (a low LMA species) is now reaching a realistic aboveground biomass above 3.5 tonnes of C/ha and realistic diameter and age distribution inside the final population (see figure 8).

Figure 8: TROLL simulations with allometry from Reich 1991 and new model M11 for Symphonia sp 1 over 500 years. Top graphics present aboveground biomass (AGB) for Symphonia simulations inside TROLL over 500 years with respectively Reichs 1991 allometry (A) and model M11 (B). Bottom graphics show respectively age (C) and diameter at breast heigh (D) histograms for Symphonia simulations inside TROLL over 500 years with both Reichs 1991 allometry and model M11.
